The '''curlew sandpiper''' ('''''Calidris ferruginea''''') is a small [[wader]]. It is a long-distance [[bird migration|migrant]], breeding in the [[bog]]s and [[Coastal plain|coastal lowlands]] of the [[Siberia]]n Arctic, arriving there in June and staying to August or September. After the breeding season, it migrates south to spend the winter in [[Africa]] and along the coasts of [[Oceania]] and southern [[Eurasia]], occupying tidal [[mudflat]]s and [[Salt evaporation pond|saltpans]].

It has three main [[plumage]]s that change with maturity and season. The non-breeding plumage shows brown-greyish [[upperparts]] and white {{Birdgloss|underparts}}. The breeding plumage is much more striking, with the entire front tinted a [[rufous|deep rusty colour]], more intensely so in males. The first-year bird does not migrate or breed, instead remaining in its [[Overwintering|overwintering range]] throughout [[Seasonal breeder|breeding season]]. It may occasionally moult into its breeding plumage, which is largely similar to that of an adult but with white spots on the chest. The non-breeding juvenile plumage is also like that of an adult, except with creamy-coloured streaking on the breast and pale fringes on some of the wing feathers, leading to a scaly appearance. Adults superficially resemble the larger but shorter-billed [[red knot]] and the [[red phalarope]] in breeding plumage, and [[dunlin]] and [[stilt sandpiper]] while not breeding. Juveniles may be confused with the larger and yellow-legged juvenile [[Ruff (bird)|ruff]], or the juvenile dunlin, which has a streaked chest.

The curlew sandpiper's [[courtship behaviour]] is complex and involves several distinct displays. In one, the male constructs a faux nest on the ground to present to the female. Another is a graceful aerial chase accompanied by frequent warbling calls. In a third, the male dances around the female on the ground, displaying his tail feathers and rump; this display sometimes culminates in [[copulation]]. The female almost always lays one [[Clutch (eggs)|clutch]] of eggs, usually around the end of June, which hatch after 20 days and fully fledge at 14–20 days. Chicks are [[Precociality and altriciality|relatively mature and mobile]] at birth. The curlew sandpiper's breeding success is linked to the population of [[Lemming|lemmings]]; in years with many lemmings, predators will hunt lemmings instead. It is [[omnivorous]], foraging in wetlands in large flocks for various [[invertebrate]]s, including [[crab]]s and [[insect]]s.

It is listed as a [[vulnerable species]] on the [[IUCN Red List]], as land development and the invasive [[smooth cordgrass]] have caused significant habitat loss to its overwintering and migratory sites, and [[climate change]] has lowered its breeding productivity. The curlew sandpiper has an estimated annual survival rate of 75–80%.

==Taxonomy and etymology==
The curlew sandpiper was [[species description|formally described]] in 1763 by the Danish ornithologist [[Erik Pontoppidan]] under the [[binomial name]] ''Tringa ferrugineus'',<ref>{{cite book |last=Pontoppidan |first=Erik |author-link=Erik Pontoppidan |title=Den Danske Atlas eller Konge-Riget Dannemark |trans-title=The Danish Atlas or Kingdom of Denmark |url=https://gdz.sub.uni-goettingen.de/id/PPN391287532?tify={%22pages%22:[728]} |year=1763 |volume=1 |page=624 |location=Kiøbenhavn |publisher=Godiche |language=da}}</ref> later designated ''Tringa ferruginea'' by [[Morten Thrane Brünnich]] in 1764.<ref>{{Cite taxon|avibase|access-date=2026-04-27|title=Curlew Sandpiper|url=https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=143A681C9BCE9A20&sec=summary}}</ref> Historically, it was often placed in the genus ''[[Tringa]]'' along with other small sandpipers; in 1816, [[Louis Pierre Vieillot]] even considered it the [[type species]] of that genus.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Systematics § Systematics History}} It was later moved to the genus ''[[Calidris]].''<ref>{{cite journal | last=Merrem | first=Blasius | author-link=Blasius Merrem | date=1804 | title=Naturgeschichte | language=de | journal=[[Allgemeine Literatur-Zeitung]] | volume=168 | at=Col. 542 | url=https://api.digitale-sammlungen.de/iiif/presentation/v2/bsb10502034/canvas/453/view |quote=Knuſſel, Calidris. Schnabel walzenförmig, gegen die Spitze hin dicker, glatt. Mittlere und äuſsere Zehe etwas verbunden. ''Tringa calidris, arenaria'' u. a.|trans-quote=Knussel, Calidris. Beak cylindrical, becoming thicker toward the tip, smooth. Middle and outer toes somewhat connected. ''Tringa calidris, arenaria'' and others.|issn=1861-6682|trans-title=Natural history}} Published anonymously.</ref><ref name="ioc">{{cite web | editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | date=2026 | title=Sandpipers, snipes, coursers | work=IOC World Bird List Version 15.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/sandpipers/ | publisher=[[International Ornithologists' Union]] | access-date=2026-04-27 | archive-date=2024-08-02 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240802230531/https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/sandpipers/ | url-status=live }}</ref> The genus name is from [[Ancient Greek]] {{Lang|grc-Latn|kalidris}} or {{Lang|grc-Latn|skalidris}}, a term used by [[Aristotle]] for some grey waterside birds. The [[specific epithet]] ''ferruginea'' is from [[Latin]] {{Lang|la|ferrugo}}'', {{Lang|la|ferruginis}}'', "iron rust", referring to the bird's colour in breeding plumage.<ref name="job">{{cite book |last=Jobling |first=James A. |title=The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names |url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling |date=2009 |edition=1st |pages=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n84 84], [https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n159 159] |location=London |publisher=[[Christopher Helm]] |isbn=978-1-4081-2501-4}}</ref> The curlew sandpiper has [[Monotypic taxon|no recognised subspecies]].<ref name=ioc/> Within the genus ''Calidris'', the curlew sandpiper is most closely related to the [[stilt sandpiper]]; together they form part of a small clade also including the [[spoon-billed sandpiper]], [[Temminck's stint]], [[red-necked stint]], and [[long-toed stint]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Gibson | first1=Rosemary | last2=Baker | first2=Allan | date=2012 | title=Multiple gene sequences resolve phylogenetic relationships in the shorebird suborder Scolopaci (Aves: Charadriiformes) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=64 | issue=1 | pages=66–72 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2012.03.008| pmid=22491071 |eissn=1095-9513|issn=1055-7903}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Černý |first=David |last2=Natale |first2=Rossy |date=2022 |title=Comprehensive taxon sampling and vetted fossils help clarify the time tree of shorebirds (Aves, Charadriiformes) |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=177 |article-number=107620 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2022.107620 |issn=1055-7903 }}</ref> The curlew sandpiper occasionally [[Hybridisation in shorebirds|hybridises]] with [[sharp-tailed sandpiper|sharp-tailed]] and [[pectoral sandpiper|pectoral]] sandpipers, producing the hybrids [[Hybridisation in shorebirds#Cooper's sandpiper|Cooper's sandpiper]] and [[Cox's sandpiper]], respectively.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Cox | first=John B. | year=1989 | title=Notes on the affinities of Cooper's and Cox's sandpipers | journal=[[South Australian Ornithologist]] | volume=30 | pages=169–181 | url=https://resources.birdssa.au/images/saopdfs/Volume30/1989V30P169.pdf |issn=0038-2973}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| last=Cox | first=John B. |year=1990 |title=The measurements of Cooper's Sandpiper and the occurrence of a similar bird in Australia |journal=South Australian Ornithologist |volume=31 | pages=38–43 |url=https://resources.birdssa.au/images/saopdfs/Volume31/1990V31P038.pdf }}</ref> Hybrids with the [[dunlin]] and [[white-rumped sandpiper]] have also been observed, though they are rare.<ref>{{Cite book |last=McCarthy |first=Eugene M. |title=Handbook of Avian Hybrids of the World |date=2006 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-518323-8 |location=Oxford, New York |page=169}}</ref>

==Description==
[[File:Calidris ferruginea - Yi-Kai Tea - 242415433 (cropped portrait).jpeg|alt=A curlew sandpiper in flight over the ocean. On its wing, there is a striking white stripe going from near the tip of the wing to near the rump.|left|thumb|250x250px|A curlew sandpiper in flight, displaying its prominent white wingstripe and rump.]]
The curlew sandpiper is a small [[wader]] 18–23&nbsp;cm in length and weighing 44–117 g.<ref name="HBW">{{cite book |last1=Hoyo |first1=Josep del |last2=Elliott |first2=Andrew |last3=Sargatal |first3=Jordi |title=Handbook of the Birds of the World: Hoatzin to Auks |publisher=[[Lynx Edicions]] |publication-place=Barcelona |date=1992 |isbn=978-84-87334-20-7 |volume=3 |pages=524–525}}</ref> It has a wingspan of 38–46&nbsp;cm,<ref>{{Cite book |last=Snow |first=David (David William) |url=http://archive.org/details/birdsofwesternpa0001snow |title=The birds of the western Palearctic |date=1998 |publisher=Oxford; New York : Oxford University Press |others=Internet Archive |isbn=978-0-19-854099-1}}</ref> a bill length of 32–44&nbsp;mm, and a {{Birdgloss|tarsus}} (the bone between the "knee" and the "ankle"{{Efn|What looks like the "knee" of the bird is actually the ankle, as for all birds, the knee bends backwards and is tucked inside the body. This means that the "ankle" of the bird would be the foot of the bird, and the apparent "foot" would actually be the bird's toes.<ref>{{cite web | last=Garrod | first=Professor Ben | title=Do birds have knees? Why do they look so strange? | website=Discover Wildlife | date=2024-10-31 | url=https://www.discoverwildlife.com/animal-facts/birds/do-birds-have-knees | access-date=2026-03-06}}</ref>}}) length of 26–34&nbsp;mm.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Wells |first=David |title=The birds of the Thai-Malay Peninsula: covering Burma and Thailand south of the eleventh parallel, Peninsular Malaysia and Singapore |last2=Round |first2=Philip D. |last3=Treesucon |first3=Uthai |date=1999 |publisher=Academic Press |isbn=978-0-12-742961-8 |location=San Diego}}</ref>has a black bill, dark brown [[Iris (anatomy)|irises]], and dark grey to black feet.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Bare Parts}} All plumages have a large white patch on the rump, occasionally barred with red in some adults, and in flight show a distinctive white stripe going across the wing.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Field Identification § Identification}} Like most waders, the curlew sandpiper has seasonal plumages and [[Moulting|moults]] yearly, shedding its old feathers and growing new ones. For example, to attain its breeding plumage,will have to first complete the pre-breeding moult; to attain its non-breeding plumage, it will have to complete the post-breeding moult.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Moults, and Structure § Moults}}

The non-breeding plumage has greyish upperparts, and white underparts with some pale grey streaks; however, as feather wear increases, it slowly becomes more brown. The centres of its upperpart feathers are darker, especially on the {{Birdgloss|crown|top of the head}}, causing its upperparts to look mottled. The tail's underside and the {{Birdgloss|rump}} are white, with broad, pale grey [[Rectrices|tail feathers]]. The [[Flight feather|largest feathers on its wing]] are dusky with white streaks along the shaft and a white tip. It has a distinctively white [[Supercilium|eyebrow]] with grey-brown feathers between the base of the bill and the eyes and around the ear.<ref>{{Harvard citation no brackets|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Definitive Basic Plumage}}. This source uses the [[Humphrey–Parkes terminology|Humphrey–Parkes moult terminology]] system, with Howell et al.'s 2003 modification. This means that, for example, the "pre-breeding moult of the yearling bird" would be called the "First Prealternate Molt".</ref> The post-breeding moult, taking place from July to November and lasting as late as April the next year for some southern populations, is a complete moult, with all feathers being replaced.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Second and Definitive Prebasic Molts}}

Occurring from January to May, the pre-breeding moult is partial, with all the body feathers and a few flight feathers being replaced.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Definitive Prealternate Molt}} The plumage of a returning breeder [[Sexual dimorphism|differs by sex]]. In the female, the front side, the entire head, and the upper back are tinted variably reddish, with grey-to-dark streaks. The feathers above the wingstripe are tipped ruddy-silver with black centres, resulting in a spotty appearance. The upper tail, the rump, and most of the wing are all nearly identical to the non-breeding appearance, except for the central tail feathers and 2 to 3 of the innermost flight feathers, which are off-black with white or ruddy fringing. Male plumage is similar to that of the female, except with the [[Rufous|rust-coloured]] tinting being almost completely opaque, and conspicuous spots above the eye and around the top of the head.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Definitive Alternate Plumage}}

The pre-juvenile moult of the chick occurs at the nest site from late June to July.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Prejuvenile (First Prebasic) Molt}} The juvenile looks similar to the adult non-breeding plumage, but the wear marks and fringing on its feathers are more evenly spread-out, resulting in a scaly and more [[Buff (colour)|buff]]-tinged appearance, and the tail feathers are slimmer. The top and back of its head are both dusky with pale creamy streaks, the back being slightly paler.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Juvenile (First Basic) Plumage}}

The post-juvenile moult occurs from October to December (and can finish as late as April) and is a partial to incomplete moult, replacing all the body feathers and some wing feathers. This moult takes place almost entirely at stopover and [[overwintering]] sites,{{Efn|Overwintering sites are the areas where a species usually stays outside of migrating and breeding.<ref>{{cite web | title=How Do Birds Survive the Winter? | website=All About Birds | date=2018-12-19 | url=https://www.allaboutbirds.org/news/how-do-birds-survive-the-winter/ | access-date=2026-02-27 | archive-date=2021-01-10 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210110012307/https://www.allaboutbirds.org/news/how-do-birds-survive-the-winter | url-status=live }}</ref>}} only rarely starting at breeding grounds.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § Preformative Molt}}

The pre-breeding moult of the first-year bird, which occurs from April to June, is absent or limited; the body feathers are largely or completely replaced, but few if any wing feathers are replaced.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § First Prealternate Molt}} The plumage of the first-time breeder is similar to the adult summer plumage, with the primary differences being white spots on the underparts, which are fully and opaquely rust-coloured, not tinted. Sex differences are also similar to that of returning breeders.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure § First Alternate Plumage}}

