=== Vocalisations ===
{{Birdsong|url=https://xeno-canto.org/species/calidris-ferruginea|species=the curlew sandpiper}}

Only the male sings.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Sounds and Vocal Behavior § Vocal Array}} Each song lasts for 10–15 seconds and consists of several parts, starting with several introductory notes, followed by multiple trilled doublets, a four-part phrase, and several drawn-out whine calls.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Vocalizations § Song}} Both genders vocalize calls.{{Efn|Calls are less complex and briefer than songs, and are usually uttered by both genders.<ref>{{cite web | last=Toms | first=Mike | title=What's the difference between a song and a call? | website=Discover Wildlife | date=2015-03-16 | url=https://www.discoverwildlife.com/animal-facts/birds/whats-the-difference-between-a-song-and-a-call | access-date=2026-03-04}}</ref>}} The alarm call is a ''whik, whik, whik'' repeated or ''wik-ki-ki-ki...'' used on the breeding grounds to warn of potential threats,{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Vocalizations § Alarm note}} and the chase call is a shrill, musical twittering given primarily by the male but occasionally by the female during courtship flights.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Vocalizations § Chase note}} The flight call is a ''chirrup'' that drops in the middle, usually uttered during takeoff.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Vocalizations § Call notes}} The whine call is a loud and ascending ''whaay, whaay, whaay'', audible hundreds of metres away, nearly identical to the [[stilt sandpiper]]'s whine.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Vocalizations § Whine note}} It is only given by the male and seems to be used for defending its territory.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Vocalizations § Whine note}}

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:Bennett-Insel 3 2014-08-25.jpg|thumb|Typical breeding habitat in the high Arctic|alt=A picture of a bog in the high Arctic]]
The curlew sandpiper can occur throughout large swathes of [[Afro-Eurasia]] during migration. It is notably missing east of the [[Verkhoyansk Range]] in eastern [[Siberia]] during migration, along with southern inland Asia. It breeds exclusively in the Siberian extreme high Arctic [[tundra]] from the [[Yamal Peninsula]] to the [[Kolyuchin Bay]].{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Distribution § Distribution of the Curlew Sandpiper}} It breeds in coastal lowlands and offshore islands, where the severe climate with harsh cold winds and short growing period prevents the growth of shrubs, and melting snow overlying the [[permafrost]] creates boggy conditions.<ref name="Cramp" /> The nest is typically placed on the margins of wet hollows or pools, or on the gentle slopes of hummocks, often close to the nests of ''[[Pluvialis]]'' plovers like [[grey plover]] or [[Pacific golden plover]].<ref name="Cramp" />

Its non-breeding range includes coastal regions of west Africa (from [[Mauritania]] to [[Gabon]] and including [[Cape Verde]]) and southern Africa (inland throughout [[Mozambique]] to [[Namibia]] to [[South Africa]], and north through [[Uganda]] to [[Kenya]]). It is additionally present, albeit more rarely, inland from [[Niger]] to [[Chad]], throughout the [[Republic of the Congo]] to [[Angola]], and the [[Nile]] from [[Sudan]] to [[Egypt]] and southeastern [[Tunisia]]. It is rarer along the coasts of [[Australasia]], as well as inland [[Victoria (state)|Victoria]] and [[New South Wales]]. In [[New Zealand]], it can be found on the southeastern coast of the [[South Island]] and the entire coastline of the [[North Island]]. It also overwinters in coastal [[South Asia]] as well as [[Southeast Asia]]. It does not overwinter in the rest of [[Eurasia]]. The curlew sandpiper is a scarce migratory [[Vagrancy (biology)|vagrant]] in [[North America]], especially along the [[East Coast of the United States|Atlantic Seaboard]].{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Distribution § Nonbreeding Range}}

During the non-breeding season, it is commonly found along sheltered [[mudflat]]s, as well as [[Salt flat|salt pans]] and [[wetland]] edges. While inland, it occupies the edges of various bodies of water, especially if they have muddy or sandy margins; it is also found along sewage ponds.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Habitat § Habitat in Overwintering Range}} It occupies coastal and inland wetlands during migration,{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Habitat § Habitat in Migration}} and during breeding it mostly remains in lowland tundra near [[bog]]s, depressions, or pools, away from scrub and other dense vegetation.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Habitat § Habitat in Breeding Range}}

=== Migration ===
The curlew sandpiper shows little fidelity to nesting sites, making it hard to predict where a specimen overwinters based on its breeding area. The fidelity to overwintering sites is much higher: adults tend to prefer overwintering in the same regions and resting at stopovers at the same points, and males are more faithful to their sites compared to females. Both sexes have their breeding plumage by the time they arrive at their breeding sites.<ref name="TomkovichSoloviev1994">{{Cite journal |last=Tomkovich |first=P. S. |last2=Soloviev |first2=M. Yu. |date=1994 |title=Site fidelity in High Arctic breeding waders |journal=[[Ostrich (journal)|Ostrich]] |volume=65 |issue=2 |pages=174–180 | doi=10.1080/00306525.1994.9639680 }}</ref>

Males depart from the breeding grounds when the female starts incubating, and females depart either when breeding fails or when the young successfully fledge. A curlew sandpiper chick migrates south soon after learning to fly; however, it does not migrate back for breeding during their first breeding season, instead remaining in their overwintering range.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Movements and Migration § Migration Overview}}<ref name="TomkovichSoloviev1994" /> In Western Europe, post-breeding migration commences with adults arriving in July, and largely departing onwards before juveniles pass through in August and September.<ref name="Cramp">{{cite book | editor1-last=Cramp | editor1-first=Stanley | editor1-link=Stanley Cramp | year=1983 | chapter=''Calidris ferruginea'' Curlew Sandpiper | title=Handbook of the Birds of Europe the Middle East and North Africa. The Birds of the Western Palearctic | volume=III: Waders to Gulls | location=Oxford | publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] | isbn=978-0-19-857506-1 | pages=339–345 }}</ref>

==Behaviour==
[[File:Curlew_Sandpiper_(Calidris_ferruginea)_(8066906558).jpg|thumb|A juvenile preening|alt=A juvenile curlew sandpiper standing in water, cleaning its tail feathers with its beak.]]
The curlew sandpiper appears to be largely [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]]; however, its breeding habits are not well studied. Its ground movements are similar to that of other waders: walking, running, and wading.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Behavior § Locomotion}} Its flight speed during migration has been estimated to be around 70–75&nbsp;km/h.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1972 |title=The unprecedented westward migration of Curlew Sandpipers in autumn 1969 |url=https://britishbirds.co.uk/journal/article/unprecedented-westward-migration-curlew-sandpipers-autumn-1969 |access-date=2026-02-06 |website=[[British Birds (magazine)|British Birds]] |language=en|issn=0007-0335 | url-access=subscription }}</ref> It practices [[preening]] and bathing, sometimes scratching its head with its claws and dipping its head in the water to clean it. It mainly roosts at high tide in large mixed-species flocks on sandbars, lagoon islets, and occasionally dunes, reefs, or [[beach wrack]].{{Efn|Beach wrack is the name for the organic debris washed ashore on beaches, usually consisting various [[seaweeds]] and marine plants like [[eelgrass]] or [[surfgrass]].<ref>{{cite web | first=Nick | last =Baca | title=Beach Wrack | website=Salish Magazine | date=2021-09-03 | url=https://salishmagazine.org/beach-wrack/ | access-date=2026-03-10}}</ref>}}{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Behavior § Sleeping, Roosting}} If disturbed while resting, it will often stretch its wings over its back before hopping on one leg or walking away.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Maclean |first=Gordon L. |url=https://archive.org/details/robertsbirdsofso0000robe_i8n2 |title=Roberts' Birds of Southern Africa |last2=Newman |first2=Kenneth |last3=Lockwood |first3=Geoff |date=1988 |publisher=New Holland |isbn=978-1-85368-037-3 |edition=5. ed. First publ. in th UK |location=London |page=246}}</ref>

===Breeding===
The curlew sandpiper forms pairs during northwards migration.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Portenko |first=Leonid A. |date=1968 |title=Studien an einigen seltenen Limicolen aus dem nördlichen und östlichen Sibirien III |journal=[[Journal of Ornithology|Journal für Ornithologie]] |language=de |volume=109 |issue=1 |pages=96–115 |doi=10.1007/BF01678109 |issn=1439-0361|trans-title=Studies on some rare waders from northern and eastern Siberia III}}</ref> Pairs usually arrive at their breeding site in early June and perform [[Courtship display|courtship]] in mid-June. The female moves around an area of a few hectares, feeding, and the male follows her attentively, trailing her 3–6 m away, occasionally giving partial or complete songs and conducting various types of courtship behaviour.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Courtship Behavior}}

During aerial courtship, the male pursues the female in long chases, occasionally catching up. When he catches up, he lifts his wings horizontally and glides towards the female while warbling and occasionally performing his chase call (the female also, although more rarely, performs the chase call). The aerial chase closely resembles chases during territorial conflicts, though the latter is more erratic, with sharper turns and gyrations. After the pair lands, the male then begins one of the ground courtship displays.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Courtship Behavior § Aerial courtship}} During the pre-nesting period, the male intermittently assumes a "courtship" stance known as the ground courtship attitude (lowered head, ruffled scapulars and back feathers, and bent legs, resulting in a hunched appearance) during feeding. It is often followed by a full ground courtship display and seems to represent increased [[libido]] in males.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Courtship Behavior § Ground courtship attitude}}

The nest-cup display, one of two ground courtship displays, is often preceded by courtship attitude behaviour. The male, in short bursts, moves across the tundra, eventually stepping into a small depression. Once in the depression, he settles down as if it were a nest, folding his wings over his back and raising his tail. He proceeds to wag his wings and tail side to side, occasionally crouching and kicking up lichen and moss with his claws. He then stands up, picks various bits of vegetation from around him, and deposits them by his feet in the faux nest. Even if the bit of vegetation slips, he still mimes the motion of tossing it into the nest. This sequence is typically followed by him stamping his claws or repeating the crouching motion from earlier. During the sequence, he occasionally makes whine notes and trill calls. This display is not an act of nest-building, as the male performs it several times, each in different locations. Females are usually a few metres away but do not seem to pay full attention to the display.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Courtship Behavior § Ground courtship: nest-cup display}}

The precopulatory display precedes [[Copulation (zoology)|copulation]] and is described as elaborate, beginning with both birds standing near each other. The male raises the wing closer to the female, reaching an angle of about 60–70° with the horizontal, and raises the other wing to match it. He also raises his head and lowers and fans his tail. Following this, he gives a short series of warbling calls and sways back and forth, alternating between being behind her and in front of her. He attempts to display his fanned tail and rump to the female by keeping his back always facing her. The female, who has so far ignored him, dashes and thrusts her head towards the male's rump, occasionally overshooting such that her head ends up along the male's flank instead. After around a minute of this display, the female turns away, and the male, with his wings still held up high, approaches to mount and copulate.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Courtship Behavior § Ground courtship: precopulatory behavior}}

[[File:Calidris ferruginea MHNT.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7 | An egg|alt=A curlew sandpiper egg. It is pyriform and yellow with brown spots of varying size.]]

The breeding grounds are occupied from June until late August.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964|loc=Chronology of Events Near Barrow, Alaska, 1962}} Nesting sites are usually located at the edge of a marsh or pool or on dry patches of tundra, often near nests of other curlew sandpipers. [[Clutch (eggs)|Clutches]] consist of 3–4 eggs (average 3.76) and are typically laid over the course of three days. The first brood is regularly laid from late June to July, with especially early breeders laying eggs only 5–6 days after arriving and the majority of pairs finishing around the end of June.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Breeding § Phenology}} A second brood may occur for some birds nesting in the far south of their breeding range if the first is unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Tomkovich |first=P.S. |last2=Soloviev |first2=M.Y. |date=2006 |title=Curlew Sandpipers ''Calidris ferruginea'' on their breeding grounds: schedule and geographic distribution in the light of their breeding system |url=https://istina.msu.ru/media/publications/articles/6c9/012/2503764/C_ferruginea_tomksoloviev_IWS.pdf |journal=International Wader Studies |volume=19 |pages=19–26|issn=1354-9944}}</ref> Eggs are slightly pear-shaped and olive-coloured with large dark olive or brown splotches, with more splotches on the broad end, giving them a roughly continuous shade of olive-brown.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Breeding § Eggs}} The female incubates the eggs alone for 20 days.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Breeding § Phenology}}

At birth, the nestlings are [[precocial|relatively mature and mobile]], covered with [[down feathers|down]], and begin to wander from the nest after drying. On average, the nestling weighs 8.2 g, with a bill length of 10.8&nbsp;mm, a tarsus length of 23.2 mm, and a wingspan of 17&nbsp;mm. The rate of growth is proportional to the temperature, with lower temperatures coinciding with slower growth and vice versa. The female leads the nestlings to good feeding habitats, and they become completely independent at 14–20 days of age. By the time they fledge, the nestlings weigh on average 49.6 g, with a bill length of 27.8&nbsp;mm, tarsus length of 30.8&nbsp;mm, and a wingspan of 94.5&nbsp;mm.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Schekkerman |first=H. |last2=Van Roomen |first2=M.W.J. |last3=Underhill |first3=L.G. |date=1998 |title=Growth, behaviour of broods and weather-related variation in breeding productivity of Curlew Sandpipers ''Calidris ferruginea'' |url=https://research.rug.nl/en/publications/growth-behaviour-of-broods-and-weather-related-variation-in-breed/ |journal=[[Ardea (journal)|Ardea]] |volume=86 |issue=2 |pages=153–168 |issn=0373-2266}}</ref>

=== Territorial behaviour ===
The male curlew sandpiper is territorial, chasing off other birds, including dunlin, [[Baird's sandpiper]]s, and pectoral sandpipers.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964||loc=Territorial Behavior}} Territories are 1.6–4.0 [[hectare]]s in size for pairs and smaller for individuals.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964||loc=Territorial Behavior § Defended area}} The male performs aerial displays and whine notes to announce territory, chasing intruders up to the edge of his territory, in flight or on the ground, similar to the aerial courtship display except more erratic, jagged, and rapid.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964||loc=Territorial Behavior § Ground announcement}} He stops his chases at the territorial boundary, suggesting awareness of his neighbour's territory. Upon concluding a chase, he often performs a flight song while returning.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964||loc=Territorial Behavior § Territorial flight displays}} An aggressive ground display was observed in a 1964 study; it consists of the male lowering his head and neck parallel to the ground and pulling them back towards his body, and fanning his tail before running towards the invading bird.{{sfn|Holmes|Pitelka|1964||loc=Territorial Behavior}}

===Feeding and diet===
While overwintering and migrating, the curlew sandpiper forages in large flocks (often [[Mixed-species foraging flock|mixed-species]]) of up to thousands on tidal flats, shallows, marshes, salt flats, and sewage lagoons, probing the ground for food,{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Diet and Foraging}} sometimes swimming while feeding.<ref>{{cite book | editor1-last=Higgins | editor1-first=P.J. | editor2-last=Davies | editor2-first=S.J.J.F. | year=1996 | chapter=''Calidris ferruginea'' Curlew Sandpiper | title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand & Antarctic Birds | volume=3, Snipe to pigeons | location=Melbourne, Victoria | publisher=Oxford University Press | isbn=978-0-19-553070-4 | pages=315-326 [321] | chapter-url=https://www.nzbirdsonline.org.nz/assets/95597/1691911020-189_curlew-20sandpiper.pdf }}</ref> In mixed-species wader flocks, it is one of the dominant species, winning 83% of aggressive interactions with dunlin; individual birds feeding on detritus show significantly higher aggression toward dunlin than groups do.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Stawarczyk |first=Tadeusz |date=1984 |title=Aggression and Its Suppression in Mixed-Species Wader Flocks |journal=Ornis Scandinavica |volume=15 |issue=1 |pages=29-32 |doi=10.2307/3675999 |jstor=3675999 |via=[[JSTOR]]}}</ref> While breeding, it forages alone or in much smaller groups.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Diet and Foraging}} Its diet consists of [[insect]]s and other small [[invertebrate]]s such as [[crab]]s, [[Mollusca|molluscs]], and [[worm]]s, supplemented with various seeds.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Diet and Foraging § Diet}} As the female is larger and longer-billed than the male, she is more likely to wade and tends to take larger, more calorically rewarding prey; in a study at [[Langebaan Lagoon Marine Protected Area|Langebaan Lagoon]], South Africa, she ate half as many [[Gastropoda|gastropods]], double the mass of [[Crustacean|crustaceans]], and 25% fewer [[polychaete]]s.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Diet and Foraging § Diet § Quantitative Analysis}} Juveniles forage significantly more slowly than adults, likely due to inexperience and reduced motivation: unlike adults preparing to return to breeding grounds, juveniles typically remain on the overwintering grounds throughout the breeding season.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Diet and Foraging § Feeding § Food Capture and Consumption}}

=== Survival ===
[[File:Curlew Sandpiper ( Calidris ferruginea ) Juvenile ... Bridlington , Yorkshire (53214618421).jpg|thumb|A juvenile|alt=A juvenile curlew sandpiper, standing on the ground.]]
The curlew sandpiper has an estimated annual survival rate of 75–80%, with the oldest observed individual being 19 years old.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Dawes |first=J. |date=2011 |title=The declining population of Curlew Sandpiper ''Calidris ferruginea'' indicates that it may now be endangered in New South Wales |url=https://awsg.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2020/11/Stilt-60.pdf |journal=[[The Stilt]] |volume=60 |pages=9–13|issn=0726-1888}}</ref> Its breeding success has not been directly measured.{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Demography and Populations}}

The curlew sandpiper is illegally trapped along the south-east coast of [[India]] around [[Point Calimere]] and hunted while migrating through the [[Yellow Sea|Yellow]] and [[East China Sea|East China]] seas.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Threats}} Waders are also occasionally targeted in the [[Arabian Peninsula]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Use and Trade}} It is additionally hunted along the [[Asian–East African Flyway]], however the scope of hunting is not well known.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Threats}} [[Heavy metal pollution|Heavy-metal pollution]] may be linked to adverse health effects; concentrations of [[chromium]], [[lead]], and [[cadmium]] in faecal samples from birds on the west coast of India were found to be increasing from 2019 to 2023.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Aarif |first=K. M. |last2=Rubeena |first2=K. A. |last3=Nefla |first3=Aymen |last4=Musilova |first4=Zuzana |last5=Musil |first5=Petr |last6=Bin Muzaffar |first6=Sabir |date=2025 |title=Bio-concentration of hazardous metals in migrant shorebirds in a key conservation reserve and adjoining areas on the west coast of India |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0147651325000260 |journal=Ecotoxicology and Environmental Safety |volume=289 |article-number=117690 |doi=10.1016/j.ecoenv.2025.117690 |issn=0147-6513 |pmid=39793283}}</ref>

The reproductive success of this species is strongly related to the population of lemmings, specifically the [[West Siberian lemming|West Siberian]], [[East Siberian lemming|East Siberian]] and [[Arctic lemming|Arctic]] lemmings. In years with fewer lemmings, predatory species such as [[Arctic fox]]es, [[snowy owl]]s, and [[skua]]s{{Efn|Specifically the [[long-tailed jaeger|long-tailed]], [[Parasitic jaeger|Arctic]], and [[Pomarine jaeger|Pomarine]] skuas.<ref name=":0" />}} hunt Arctic-breeding waders, including the curlew sandpiper, instead of their mammalian prey.<ref name="HBW" /><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Blomqvist |first1=S. |last2=Holmgren |first2=N. |last3=Åkesson |first3=S. |last4=Hedenström |first4=A. |last5=Pettersson |first5=J. |date=2002 |title=Indirect effects of lemming cycles on Sandpiper dynamics: 50 Years of counts from Southern Sweden |journal=[[Oecologia]] |volume=133 |issue=2 |pages=146–158 |bibcode=2002Oecol.133..146B |doi=10.1007/s00442-002-1017-2 |jstor=4223402 |pmid=28547301 |s2cid=299919}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=Tomkovich |first=P. |date=1998 |title=Breeding Conditions for Waders in Russian Tundras in 1994 |url=https://digitalcommons.usf.edu/iws/vol10/iss1/29 |journal=International Wader Studies |volume=10 |issue=1}}</ref> Arctic-breeding waders are also preyed upon by [[brown bear]]s, [[red fox]]es, [[sable]]s and [[stoat]]s.<ref name=":0" /> [[Peregrine falcon|Peregrine falcons]], [[Black falcon|black falcons]], and [[rufous-breasted sparrowhawk]]s have been observed preying upon curlew sandpipers.<ref>{{Cite web |title=''Calidris ferruginea'' (Curlew sandpiper) |url=https://www.biodiversityexplorer.info/birds/scolopacidae/calidris_ferruginea.htm#:~:text=Predators%20and%20parasites,rufiventris%20(Rufous-chested%20sparrowhawk) |access-date=2026-03-10 |website=Biodiversity Explorer |publisher=[[Iziko Museums of South Africa]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Newman |first=Mike |last2=Lindsey |first2=Ann |date=2009 |title=Curlew Sandpiper predated by a Black Falcon |url=https://www.hboc.org.au/wp-content/uploads/Black-Falcon-prey-The-Whistler-Vol-3.pdf |journal=The Whistler |volume=3 |page=58}}</ref>

The curlew sandpiper is subject to infestations from [[parasitic worm]]s, with a total of 154 worms collected from five curlew sandpipers as part of a migratory bird study in [[Tasmania]]. ''Nadejdolepis paranitidulans'' was the most common parasite, present in 87% of all birds collected. A total of five species of parasitic worms were observed, with four [[Cestoda|cestodes]] and one [[Trematoda|trematode]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Canaris |first=Ag |last2=Kinsella |first2=Jm |date=1998 |title=Helminth parasite communities in four species of shorebirds (Charadriidae) on King Island, Tasmania |url=https://figshare.utas.edu.au/articles/journal_contribution/Helminth_parasite_communities_in_four_species_of_shorebirds_Charadriidae_on_King_Island_Tasmania/24484240 |journal=Papers and Proceedings of the Royal Society of Tasmania |volume=132 |pages=49–58 |doi=10.26749/rstpp.132.49|issn=0080-4703}}</ref> The curlew sandpiper is susceptible to avian [[Avian influenza|influenza]] and [[Avian botulism|botulism]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Threats}}

==Conservation==
[[File:Spartina alterniflora.jpg|alt=An image of smooth cordgrass (scientific name Sporobolus alterniflorus) growing in the water.|thumb|Smooth cordgrass can occupy the curlew sandpiper's habitat.]]
[[BirdLife International]], which provides the [[Conservation status|IUCN conservation status]] for birds, considers the curlew sandpiper to be a [[vulnerable species]],{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=The Red List Assessment}} as despite its vast [[extent of occurrence]] (3 million [[Square kilometre|km<sup>2</sup>]]){{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Geographic Range}} and large population, over the span of 15 years the population has declined by an estimated 30–49%.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Threats}} The species is protected by the [[Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds]].{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Conservation Actions}}

The global population of the curlew sandpiper is estimated at 0.7–1.2 million individuals, including 420,000–960,000 mature birds. Approximately 300,000–400,000 individuals winter in South Africa, while another 400,000 winter across Southwest Asia, East Africa, and southern Africa. An estimated 200,000 winter in South Asia; however this figure may be an overestimate.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Population}} The [[East Asian–Australasian Flyway]] population is estimated at 120,000.<ref>{{Cite report |url=https://www.dcceew.gov.au/environment/biodiversity/publications/revision-east-asian-australasian-flyway-population-2016 |title=Revision of the East Asian-Australasian Flyway Population Estimates for 37 listed Migratory Shorebird Species |first=Lena|last=van Swinderen|first2=Birgita D.|last2=Hansen|first3=Richard A.|last3=Fuller|first4=Doug|last4=Watkins|first5=Danny I.|last5=Rogers|first6=Robert S.|last6=Clemens|first7=Mike|last7=Newman|first8=Eric J.|last8=Woehler|first9=Dan R.|last9=Weller|first10=Saundra|last10=LeClair|date=2025 |publisher=BirdLife Australia |location=Melbourne}}</ref> 

The curlew sandpiper has experienced habitat loss throughout its wintering and migratory ranges.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Threats}} On the coast of the Yellow Sea, 65% of [[Intertidal zone|intertidal]] habitats in the Yellow Sea have been lost over the past 50 years,{{Sfn|Mlodinow|Medrano|2023|loc=Conservation and Management § Effects of Human Activity}} and the amount of reclaimed land exceeds the extent of the remaining intertidal mudflats, which may have been a major cause in the population decline. In China, the rate of reclamation has slowed since 2013 and has essentially ceased as of 2018, however reclamation has continued around the [[Korean Peninsula]]. Another major factor in habitat loss is the invasive [[Sporobolus alterniflorus|smooth cordgrass]], which may make occupied mudflats unsuitable habitats.{{sfn|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Threats}} The causes of the curlew sandpiper's declining breeding productivity are not fully understood; proposed factors include fewer lemming outbreaks, a mismatch between the timing of breeding and peak insect abundance, and breeding habitat alteration, all potentially resulting from [[climate change]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Barshep |first=Yahkat |last2=Hedenström |first2=Anders |last3=Underhill |first3=Leslie Gordon |date=2011 |title=Impact of Climate and Predation on Autumn Migration of the Curlew Sandpiper |url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1675/063.034.0101 |journal=Waterbirds |language=en |volume=34 |issue=1 |pages=1–9 |doi=10.1675/063.034.0101 |issn=1524-4695 |via=[[BioOne]]}}</ref>

